Dataframe interface versus sequel — the same plan.

Take the same query, and write it two ways — once as a dataframe chain, and once as a spark dot sequel string. Catalyst rewrites both of them into the identical physical plan. And you can prove it, right there in explain — the two plans match, line for line.

This is really the payoff of the whole module. The choice between sequel and the dataframe interface is purely about readability, and team preference. It is never about performance.

Sequel shines for declarative, set-based logic, and for people who already think in sequel. The dataframe interface shines for programmatic construction — building a query up from variables, loops, and functions.

So mix them freely, within a single pipeline. The optimizer merges the plans, no matter which surface you happened to use.
